# ==========================================================================
# CPU Capacity Model Evaluation
# ==========================================================================
#
# Each scenario defines what's happening on the node:
#   kv-cpu:                  Direct KV replica CPU (total across all stores)
#   indirect-overhead:   CPU that scales with KV (dist SQL, RPC, compactions)
#   background:              CPU that does NOT scale with KV (gateway SQL, GC, jobs)
#   sql-gateway-cpu:         Gateway SQL CPU — parsing, planning, result
#                            serialization (⊆ background)
#   sql-dist-cpu:            Distributed SQL CPU — remote execution fragments
#                            (⊆ indirect-overhead)
#
# From ground truth we derive:
#   node-cpu-usage = kv-cpu + indirect-overhead + background
#   true-mult      = (kv-cpu + indirect-overhead) / kv-cpu
#   true-capacity  = (node-cpu-capacity - background) / true-mult / num-stores
#
# capacity_err = (model - true-capacity) / true-capacity * 100
#   < 0: pessimistic (safe — sheds load too early)
#   > 0: optimistic (dangerous — accepts too much work)
#
# Where each model fails:
# naive:
#   Computes mult = nodeUsage / kvCores, capacity = nodeCapacity / mult. Assumes
#   all node CPU is caused by KV work. Background inflates mult, making per-KV
#   cost too high — the more background, the worse it gets.
#
# capped_mult:
#   Like naive, but caps the multiplier at 3x. Misclassifies in both directions:
#   when mult ≤ 3x, all CPU is attributed to KV (background treated as kv
#   overhead). When mult > 3x, excess is called background (real kv overhead
#   treated as background if kv overhead exceeds 3x).
#
# sql:
#   Uses sql-gateway-cpu and sql-dist-cpu to separate background from overhead.
#   Subtracts gateway SQL as background (it doesn't move with KV), and treats
#   DistSQL as indirect overhead (it scales with KV). Fails when background is
#   dominated by non-SQL work (elastic, GC) that the model can't see.
#
# ==========================================================================
# SECTION 1: KV-only nodes — no background, all models agree
# ==========================================================================
# Pure storage nodes (e.g., serverless KV pods) with no co-located SQL gateway
# or elastic work. All CPU is direct KV + indirect overhead (Pebble
# compactions, raft, RPC). With no background to misattribute, every model
# computes the correct capacity.

# Read-heavy KV, low compaction overhead. All models correct — no background.
scenario kv-cpu=6 indirect-overhead=2 background=0 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=0 sql-dist-cpu=0
----
node-cpu: 8.00 used / 16.00 capacity (6.00 kv + 2.00 indirect + 0.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 12.00 cores/store (true-mult: 1.33)
naive:    kv-capacity: 12.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%
capped:   kv-capacity: 12.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%
sql:      kv-capacity: 12.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%

# Write-heavy KV, heavy compaction overhead (true mult = 4x).
# - naive: correct — no background to confuse it.
# - capped: true overhead exceeds the 3x cap, so it misclassifies real
#   compaction overhead as background and subtracts it.
# - sql: correct — no background to confuse it.
scenario kv-cpu=3 indirect-overhead=9 background=0 node-cpu-capacity=32 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=0 sql-dist-cpu=0
----
node-cpu: 12.00 used / 32.00 capacity (3.00 kv + 9.00 indirect + 0.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 8.00 cores/store (true-mult: 4.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 8.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%
capped:   kv-capacity: 9.67 cores/store, capacity_err: +20.83%
sql:      kv-capacity: 8.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%

# ==========================================================================
# SECTION 2: Mixed workloads with background load
# ==========================================================================
# Background CPU (elastic work, gateway SQL, etc.) doesn't move with KV
# replicas. naive treats it all as indirect to KV, inflating per-KV cost.
# capped_mult helps when the implied multiplier exceeds 3x, but can't separate
# overhead from background. SQL model uses sql-gateway-cpu to identify some
# background.

# Heavy KV, heavy elastic, light gateway. Mult well under the 3x cap.
# - naive: absorbs all 5 bg cores into per-KV cost - pessimistic.
# - capped: mult < 3x so cap never triggers, same as naive.
# - sql: subtracts 1 gateway core but the other 4 bg cores (elastic) are
#   invisible - still pessimistic, slightly less so.
scenario kv-cpu=4 indirect-overhead=3 background=5 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=1 sql-dist-cpu=1
----
node-cpu: 12.00 used / 16.00 capacity (4.00 kv + 3.00 indirect + 5.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 6.29 cores/store (true-mult: 1.75)
naive:    kv-capacity: 5.33 cores/store, capacity_err: -15.15%
capped:   kv-capacity: 5.33 cores/store, capacity_err: -15.15%
sql:      kv-capacity: 5.60 cores/store, capacity_err: -10.91%

# Elastic-dominated, minimal KV. Background (10 cores) far exceeds KV
# (1 core), so all models struggle to separate the two.
# - naive: absorbs all 10 bg cores into per-KV cost - heavily pessimistic.
# - capped: peels off 9 bg cores, but uses 3x mult instead of true 2x -
#   still pessimistic.
# - sql: only sees 1 of 10 bg cores via gateway — elastic is invisible,
#   so nearly as bad as naive.
scenario kv-cpu=1 indirect-overhead=1 background=10 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=1 sql-dist-cpu=0
----
node-cpu: 12.00 used / 16.00 capacity (1.00 kv + 1.00 indirect + 10.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 3.00 cores/store (true-mult: 2.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 1.33 cores/store, capacity_err: -55.56%
capped:   kv-capacity: 2.33 cores/store, capacity_err: -22.22%
sql:      kv-capacity: 1.67 cores/store, capacity_err: -44.44%

# Light KV, heavy gateway, light elastic.
# - naive: absorbs all 8 bg cores into per-KV cost - heavily pessimistic.
# - capped: peels off 6 of 8 bg cores - under-corrects, still pessimistic.
# - sql: sees 6 of 8 bg cores via gateway; k1 scaling inflates the
#   subtraction to cover the remaining 2 - correct.
scenario kv-cpu=2 indirect-overhead=2 background=8 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=6 sql-dist-cpu=1
----
node-cpu: 12.00 used / 16.00 capacity (2.00 kv + 2.00 indirect + 8.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store (true-mult: 2.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 2.67 cores/store, capacity_err: -33.33%
capped:   kv-capacity: 3.33 cores/store, capacity_err: -16.67%
sql:      kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%

# Heavy KV, heavy gateway, heavy elastic. Same KV as scenario 1 but
# gateway=4 vs 1 — tests the effect of increased gateway visibility.
# - naive: absorbs all 8 bg cores into per-KV cost - pessimistic.
# - capped: peels off only 2 of 8 bg cores - still pessimistic.
# - sql: sees 4 gateway cores; k1 scaling amplifies the subtraction to
#   cover most of the 8 bg cores - half the error of naive/capped.
scenario kv-cpu=4 indirect-overhead=2 background=8 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=4 sql-dist-cpu=1
----
node-cpu: 14.00 used / 16.00 capacity (4.00 kv + 2.00 indirect + 8.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 5.33 cores/store (true-mult: 1.50)
naive:    kv-capacity: 4.57 cores/store, capacity_err: -14.29%
capped:   kv-capacity: 4.67 cores/store, capacity_err: -12.50%
sql:      kv-capacity: 5.03 cores/store, capacity_err: -5.71%

# Moderate KV, heavy elastic, light gateway. Observed mult = 4x exceeds
# the 3x cap, so capped peels off some background. Sql model is nearly
# blind - only 1 of 6 bg cores is visible via gateway.
# - naive: absorbs all 6 bg cores into per-KV cost - pessimistic.
# - capped: peels off 3 of 6 bg cores - imprecise, but any correction
#   beats none when sql has so little visibility.
# - sql: sees only 1 gateway core; k1 scaling helps but still misses
#   most of the elastic background - worse than capped here.
scenario kv-cpu=3 indirect-overhead=3 background=6 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=1 sql-dist-cpu=1
----
node-cpu: 12.00 used / 16.00 capacity (3.00 kv + 3.00 indirect + 6.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 5.00 cores/store (true-mult: 2.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store, capacity_err: -20.00%
capped:   kv-capacity: 4.33 cores/store, capacity_err: -13.33%
sql:      kv-capacity: 4.25 cores/store, capacity_err: -15.00%

# Light KV, heavy DistSQL, minimal background. Very high true overhead
# (mult = 5x) from DistSQL execution of remote query fragments.
# - naive: minimal background barely inflates per-KV cost - nearly correct.
# - capped: peels off 5 cores as background, but real bg is only 1 -
#   misclassifies real DistSQL overhead as background - heavily optimistic.
# - sql: correctly treats DistSQL as indirect overhead and subtracts the
#   small gateway background - nearly correct.
scenario kv-cpu=2 indirect-overhead=8 background=1 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=1 sql-dist-cpu=6
----
node-cpu: 11.00 used / 16.00 capacity (2.00 kv + 8.00 indirect + 1.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 3.00 cores/store (true-mult: 5.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 2.91 cores/store, capacity_err: -3.03%
capped:   kv-capacity: 3.67 cores/store, capacity_err: +22.22%
sql:      kv-capacity: 3.02 cores/store, capacity_err: +0.76%

# ==========================================================================
# SECTION 3: Multi-store scenarios
# ==========================================================================

# Multi-store (2 stores), moderate KV, light gateway, light elastic.
# - naive: absorbs all 6 bg cores into per-KV cost - pessimistic.
# - capped: mult exactly at 3x cap boundary, no correction - same as naive.
# - sql: subtracts 2 gateway cores but the other 4 bg cores are invisible
#   - still pessimistic, but less so.
scenario kv-cpu=4 indirect-overhead=2 background=6 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=2 sql-gateway-cpu=2 sql-dist-cpu=1
----
node-cpu: 12.00 used / 16.00 capacity (4.00 kv + 2.00 indirect + 6.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 3.33 cores/store (true-mult: 1.50)
naive:    kv-capacity: 2.67 cores/store, capacity_err: -20.00%
capped:   kv-capacity: 2.67 cores/store, capacity_err: -20.00%
sql:      kv-capacity: 2.93 cores/store, capacity_err: -12.00%

# ==========================================================================
# SECTION 4: Edge cases
# ==========================================================================

# Zero KV CPU (startup or no replicas yet). Heavy background.
# - naive: falls back to nodeCapacity/2, ignoring background - heavily
#   optimistic.
# - capped: identifies all CPU as background but still divides by 3x
#   instead of the true 1x - heavily pessimistic.
# - sql: same fallback as naive (no SQL metrics either) - optimistic.
scenario kv-cpu=0 indirect-overhead=0 background=12 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=0 sql-dist-cpu=0
----
node-cpu: 12.00 used / 16.00 capacity (0.00 kv + 0.00 indirect + 12.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store (true-mult: 1.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 8.00 cores/store, capacity_err: +100.00%
capped:   kv-capacity: 1.33 cores/store, capacity_err: -66.67%
sql:      kv-capacity: 5.33 cores/store, capacity_err: +33.33%

# Overloaded node (usage > capacity), heavy background, no SQL metrics.
# All models are optimistic: they assume CPU would free up proportionally
# if KV scales down, but background is fixed, so less headroom exists.
# - naive: assumes all CPU scales with KV - optimistic.
# - capped: peels off 6 bg cores (real is 10), so 4 bg cores remain
#   absorbed in the multiplier - still optimistic.
# - sql: no SQL metrics available - same as naive.
scenario kv-cpu=4 indirect-overhead=4 background=10 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=0 sql-dist-cpu=0
----
node-cpu: 18.00 used / 16.00 capacity (4.00 kv + 4.00 indirect + 10.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 3.00 cores/store (true-mult: 2.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 3.56 cores/store, capacity_err: +18.52%
capped:   kv-capacity: 3.33 cores/store, capacity_err: +11.11%
sql:      kv-capacity: 3.56 cores/store, capacity_err: +18.52%

# Overloaded: background alone exceeds node capacity. True capacity = 0.
# - naive: doesn't model background, still reports positive capacity -
#   optimistic (+Inf).
# - capped: correctly detects the node is overwhelmed - correct.
# - sql: same as naive (no SQL metrics) - optimistic (+Inf).
scenario kv-cpu=1 indirect-overhead=1 background=30 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=0 sql-dist-cpu=0
----
node-cpu: 32.00 used / 16.00 capacity (1.00 kv + 1.00 indirect + 30.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 0.00 cores/store (true-mult: 2.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 0.50 cores/store, capacity_err: +Inf%
capped:   kv-capacity: 0.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%
sql:      kv-capacity: 0.50 cores/store, capacity_err: +Inf%

# 100% utilization boundary: When nodeUsage = nodeCapacity, every model
# reduces to kv / numStores. This is an algebraic identity - the
# formulas all simplify regardless of background or overhead values.
scenario kv-cpu=4 indirect-overhead=4 background=8 node-cpu-capacity=16 num-stores=1 sql-gateway-cpu=3 sql-dist-cpu=2
----
node-cpu: 16.00 used / 16.00 capacity (4.00 kv + 4.00 indirect + 8.00 background)
truth:    kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store (true-mult: 2.00)
naive:    kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%
capped:   kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%
sql:      kv-capacity: 4.00 cores/store, capacity_err: 0.00%

